 than 100 years old are not normally open for public access. However, it is possible for the nearest living relative to the patient to make an application fora1 CONC ccess to the relevant Health Authority. If you are the nearest living relative and would like us to make an application for you, please let us know. We will also need your postal address to pass on to the Health Authority.1 CONT With regard to her place of burial, I have checked our copy of the burial register for the hospital’s own burial ground. She was not buried there so I imagine that the family held a burial service at their local church or cemetery. If you can tell us wher1 CONC e her husband was living we will be able to suggest the most likely places.1 CONT Please do not hesitate to contact us again if you have further questions.1 CONT Yours sincerely,1 CONT Rebecca Jackson1 CONT Archivist1 CONT Staffordshire Record Office1 CONT Eastgate Street, Stafford ST16 2LZ1 CHAN2 DATE 08 Apr 20143 TIME 07:12:031 CREA2 DATE 13 Oct 20093 TIME 09:38:070 @N1@ NOTE1 CONT Went to America 1922, also  two sisters. Margaret and Florence May.1 CHAN2 DATE 08 Apr 20143 TIME 07:12:030 @N2@ NOTE1 CONT Born in 1898, supposed father, Terence Riley, died 1893.  Father unknown.1 CONT Apparently went AWOL during the war and turned up in America where he settled.1 CHAN2 DATE 08 Apr 20143 TIME 07:12:030 @N3@ NOTE1 CONT Went to America. California, where she worked as a nanny.1 CONT Sailed from Liverpool on SS Carmania on 29 November 1924, arriving in New York on 9 December 1924.  Aged 31 years.  First went to her sister,  Elizabeth Etches, and brother in law Gerald Denis Etches.1 CONT Found to have returned to UK for a visit as she travelled back to New York on SS Britannic in September 1930.1 CONT Made other later visits to UK.1 CHAN2 DATE 08 Apr 20143 TIME 07:12:030 @N4@ NOTE1 CONT 6 Jan 1898 - enlisted with Shropshire Light Infantry, Hanley, aged 181 CONT 1st Shropshire & Stafford Volunteer Artillery1 CONT Trade Potter1 CONT Height 5' 5 _1 CONT Weight118 lb1 CONT Complexion Fresh1 CONT Eyes Grey1 CONT Hair Brown1 CONT 8 Jan 1898 - considered 'fit' for enlistment at Lichfield - Army No - 55371 CONT Home country - 6/1/1898 - 6/11/18991 CONT South Africa - 7/11/1898 - 6/1/19031 CONT India - 7/1/1903 - 19/2/19061 CONT Home country - 20/2/1906 - 5/1/19101 CONT 18 Aug 1900- Granted ?1 CONT 7 Jun 1901- Forfeits ? pay1 CONT 3 Jun 1902- Awaiting Trial1 CONT 4 Jun 1902- Trial by F GCourt Martial for when on active service, Drunkeness and sentenced to be fined #1 and 28 days prison.1 CONT 31 Jul 1902- Paid the War Gratuity of #6.151 CONT 1 Apr 1904 - Permitted to extend Army Service to complete 8 yrs.1 CONT 1 Feb 1906- Transferred to Army Reserve1 CONT 5 Jan 1910- Discharged.  The termination of first period of engagement, 12 yrs 0 days, pension years - 8yrs 18 days.1 CONT Awarded Queens South Africa Medal with Clasps-1 CONT The medal was awarded to all who served in South Africa between 11 October 1899 and 31 May 1902 (during the Boer War).1 CONT Battle Clasps-1 CONT oCape Colony 11 October 1899 - 31 May 19021 CONT oPaardeburg,  17 - 26 February 19001 CONT oDriefontein, 10 March 1900 (Awarded to troops serving with Army Headquarters and LGen French's column which advanced from Popular Grove on 10 March 19001 CONT Awarded Kings South Africa Medal with Clasps 1901 & 1902-1 CONT This second campaign medal for the South African or 'Boer War' was instituted in 1902,  for award to all those who were in theatre on or after the 1st January 1902, and had completed 18 months service in the conflict prior to 1st June 1902. The medal wast1 CONC o recognise service in the difficult latter phases of the war, and reward those who by their long service in the field had brought the campaign to a successful conclusion. The medal was never awarded singly and was always paired with the  Queen's South Af1 CONC rica Medal.1 CONT Two clasps were awarded1 CONT South Africa 1901- All those who served in South Africa between 1st January 1901 and the 31st December 1901, both dates inclusive1 CONT South Africa 1902- All those who served in South Africa between 1st January 1902 and the 31st May 1902, both dates inclusive1 CONT Father George Salt, 6 Grove Place, Hanley1 CONT Hospital1 CONT Portsmouth7/6/1898 - 20/61898Sore throat & Mild Cold1 CONT Aldershot14/9/1899 - No Admission1 CONT S.S. Prawa? 7/11/1899  -  No Admission1 CONT Ranikhet24/11/1904 - Examined and found fit to complete ?1 CONT Fyzabad22/11/1904 - 9/12/1905 - ?1 CONT ?9/9/1898 - 15/9/1898 - Blisters on Feet1 CONT S.S.Syria7/1/1903No Admission1 CONT Ranikhet8/3/19031 CONT Barully17/10/19031 CONT . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .1 CONT 3 Nov 1914 - enlisted with King's Shropshire Light Infantry, Burslem, aged 361 CONT Army Number 157201 CONT Height 5' 61 CONT Weight 127 lb1 CONT Chest 361 CONT ComplexionFresh1 CONT Eyes Blue/Grey  (Right Eye Vision 6/Left Eye Vision 6)1 CONT Hair Brown1 CONT Trade Engineman1 CONT Wife Jane Riley1 CONT Address 11 Bradford Terrace, Birches Head, Hanley1 CONT Children  May/Eric/Dennis1 CONT Considered 'fit' for service1 CONT 16 Nov 1914 - Discharged not being likely to become an efficient soldier     Para 392 K Reg1 CONT 1 Dec 1914 - enlisted Army Reserve (Special Reservists)1 CONT Royal Garrison Artillery, enlisted Longton1 CONT Army No 54341 CONT Address 11 Bradford Terrace, Birches Head, Hanley1 CONT 4 Dec 1914- Newhaven - Gunner1 CONT Postings 1./12/1914 - 11/4/1916  Britain1 CONT 12/4/1916 -  15/10/1916 France1 CONT 16/10/1916-  20/5/1917  Britain1 CONT 21/5/1917-  13/8/1917  Britain1 CONT 21 Apr 1916- Appt Bdr1 CONT 15 May 1916- Appointed a/Copl1 CONT 12 Jun 1916- Appointed & Confirmed Corporal1 CONT 15 Jul 1916- Awaiting Trial for when on Active Service,  Drunkeness1 CONT 20 Jul 1916 - Tried and sentenced to be reduced in the Ranks to Gunner1 CONT 12 Aug 1916- Deprived 